revision.text:
'''Abu Mansur Muhammad Ibn Ahmad Daqiqi Tusi''' (935/942-976/980:<ref name="birth">Sources vary, treat all dates as estimates.</ref> {{lang-fa|ابو منصور محمد بن احمد دقیقی}}), sometimes referred to as ''Daqiqi'' (also Dakiki, Daghighi, {{lang-fa|دقیقی}}), was an early [[Persian people|Persian]]<ref>Annemarie Schimmel, ''A two-colored brocade: the imagery of Persian poetry'', University of North Carolina Press, 1992, {{ISBN|0-8078-2050-4}}, p. 116</ref> [[poet]]  who is said to have been born in [[Tus, Iran|Tus]]<ref>{{cite encyclopaedia|title=DAQĪQĪ|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/daqiqi-abu-mansur-ahmad-b|first=D.|encyclopedia=Encyclopaedia Iranica|last=Khaleghi-Motlagh|volume= 6|year=1993|quote=Various biographers have named Bukhara, Samarqand, Balḵ, Marv, and Ṭūs as his birthplace;  according to Moḥammad ʿAwfī (..), it was at Ṭūs, and for several reasons his report seems more probable.}}</ref><ref>Zabihullah Safa /Tarikh-e adabiat-e Iran / P409</ref> in [[Iran]];  or  in [[Balkh]],<ref>Daqiqi is always known as ''Daqiqi Balkhi''. He was born in Balkh. Here's an article of Dr. Nasrullah Poorjawadi, an Iranian writer and scholar [http://www.mehrnews.ir/fa/NewsPrint.aspx?NewsID=392655 LINK] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071220112805/http://www.mehrnews.ir/fa/NewsPrint.aspx?NewsID=392655 |date=December 20, 2007 }}</ref> located in modern-day [[Afghanistan]]; as well as in [[Samarqand]] or [[Bukhara]], both in today's [[Uzbekistan]] and [[Merv|Marv]] in today's [[Turkmenistan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/daqiqi-abu-mansur-ahmad-b|title=DAQĪQĪ, ABŪ MANṢŪR AḤMAD  – Encyclopaedia Iranica|first=|last=electricpulp.com|date=|website=www.iranicaonline.org}}</ref>

Daqiqi wrote an [[Epic poetry|epic]] history of [[Iran]] which is begun by history of Zarathushtra and Gashtasb.  Questions have been raised as to whether Daqiqi harboured some Zoroastrian beliefs, or was simply promoting [[Sassanian]] cultural trends in the wake of [[Samanid]] domination.<ref>''Humanism in the Renaissance of Islam'', by Joel L. Kraemer, pg. 92</ref> Nevertheless, he is viewed to have been a Zoroastrian convert to Islam.<ref>E.J. Brill's first encyclopaedia of Islam, 1913-1936, Volume 2 By Martijn Theodoor Houtsma, pg. 100</ref> A large number of couplets by him were included in the epic [[Shahname]] (Book of Kings) by the Persian epic poet [[Ferdowsi]].  Daqiqi was murdered by his favorite slave.<ref>''Classical Persian Literature'', by Arthur John Arberry, pg. 41</ref>

