'''Aetnaeus''' ([[Greek language|Greek]]: {{lang|grc|Αἰτναῖος}}) was an [[epithet]] given to several [[Greek mythology|Greek]] and [[Roman mythology|Roman]] gods and mythical beings connected with [[Mount Etna|Mount Aetna]],<ref>{{Citation  | last = Schmitz  | first = Leonhard  | contribution = Aetnaeus  | editor-last = Smith  | editor-first = William  | title = [[Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology]]  | volume = 1  | pages = 54  | place = Boston  | year = 1870  | contribution-url = http://quod.lib.umich.edu/m/moa/acl3129.0001.001/69?page=root;size=100;view=image}}</ref> such as [[Zeus]], of whom there was a statue on Mount Aetna, and to whom a festival was celebrated there, called Aetnaea,<ref>Schol. ''ad Pind. Ol.'' vi. 162</ref> [[Hephaestus]], who had his workshop in the mountain, and a temple near it,<ref>[[Claudius Aelianus|Aelian]], ''Hist. An.'' xi. 3</ref> and the [[Cyclops]].<ref>[[Virgil]], ''[[Aeneid]]'' viii. 440, xi. 263, iii. 768</ref><ref>Ov. ''Ex Pont.'' ii. 2.115</ref>

