[[file:Mezquita Maicao Colombia Yuri Romero Picon.JPG|200px|thumb|The Mosque of [[Omar Ibn Al-Khattab]] is the third largest mosque in Latin America.]] {{islam by country}}
The statistics for '''Islam in Colombia''' estimate a total [[Muslim]] population of 14,000 (0.03%) according to a [[Pew Research Center]] report.<ref>[http://pewforum.org/uploadedfiles/Topics/Demographics/Muslimpopulation.pdf Muslimpopulation.pdf] pewforum.org</ref> There are a number of [[Islamic]] communities in [[Colombia]], the most important of which, according to their size, are in [[Bogotá#Religion|Bogotá]], [[Maicao]] and [[Buenaventura, Valle del Cauca|Buenaventura]]. There are also Islamic centers in [[San Andrés, San Andrés y Providencia|San Andrés]], [[Nariño]], [[Santa Marta]] and [[Cartagena, Colombia|Cartagena]].
There are also primary and secondary Islamic schools in Bogotá and [[Maicao]]. Maicao plays host to the continent's third largest mosque, the [[Mosque of Omar Ibn Al-Khattab]]. Most Muslims in Colombia are descendants of Arab immigrants from Syria, Lebanon, and Palestine during the late 19th to early 20th century.<ref>{{Cite book| last=Klich | first=Ignacio, Jeff Lesser | year=1992 | title=Arab and Jewish immigrants in Latin America | publisher=Routledge| isbn=0-7146-4873-6| page=58}}</ref>
The Afro-Colombian Muslims in Buenaventura, Colombia’s main Pacific port city, have over the years embraced the teachings of the [[Nation of Islam]], mainstream [[Sunni]] Islam, and the [[Shia]] denomination <ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/jan/23/colombia-islam-muslim-buenaventura | title=How Islam took root in one of South America’s most violent cities | date=January 17, 2017 | accessdate=January 17, 2017}}</ref>
The [[Ahmadiyya]] Community also has a presence in the country.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.prensalibre.com/noticias/Islamismo-pretende-llegar-varios-paises_0_820118010.html | title=Islamismo pretende llegar a varios países | date=November 30, 2014 | accessdate=July 14, 2014}}</ref>
